# Recreate `vehicle_angular_velocity` from FIFO gyro + tunable filter YAML

## Context

For the oddjob vibe analysis we want to *retune the PX4 gyro/dgyro filters offline* and see the
effect on the IMU signal (notably the ~99.4 Hz vibration line) without reflashing/reflying. To trust
any retuning, we must first prove we can reproduce PX4's `vehicle_angular_velocity` exactly from the
raw `sensor_gyro_fifo`, using the same filter chain, the same calibration, and the same output rate.

This delivers: (1) a Python tool that recreates `vehicle_angular_velocity.xyz` (gyro) and
`.xyz_derivative` (dgyro) from the FIFO, (2) a YAML to change `IMU_GYRO_CUTOFF`, `IMU_DGYRO_CUTOFF`,
`IMU_GYRO_NF0_FRQ/BW` (+ NF1) and re-filter, and (3) verification plots showing the recreation matches
the logged signal. Test log: `OD1A079_nexus_endurance.ulg`. (Coning compensation is not part of
`vehicle_angular_velocity` — it only affects `vehicle_imu` delta-angle — so it is correctly ignored.)

User decisions: **full-fidelity match** (board rotation + static offset + EKF bias) and
**validate-then-retune** (seed YAML with the log's real params so the first run proves correctness,
then edit to explore; optional `candidate:` overlay for what-if tunings).

